In [[mathematics]], especially in [[topology]], '''equidimensionality''' is a property of a space that the local dimension is the same everywhere.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.mathematik.uni-kl.de/pub/scripts/wirthm/Top/topology.pdf|title=A Topology Primer: Lecture Notes 2001/2002|publisher=|author=Wirthmüller, Klaus | page=90 }}</ref>
==Definition== A [[topological space]] ''X'' is said to be equidimensional if for all points ''p'' in ''X'' the [[dimension]] at ''p'' that is, dim&nbsp;''p''(''X'') is [[constant (mathematics)|constant]]. The [[Euclidean space]] is an example of an equidimensional space. The [[disjoint union]] of two spaces ''X'' and ''Y'' (as topological spaces) of different dimension is an example of a non-equidimensional space.
==Cohen–Macaulay ring== An [[algebraic variety]] whose [[coordinate ring]] is a [[Cohen–Macaulay ring]] is equidimensional.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.math.tifr.res.in/~anands/connectedness.pdf |title=Hartshorne’s Connectedness Theorem|publisher=|author=Anand P. Sawant | page=3}}</ref>
